SPECIES COMMENTS: My Rock Wren quest took me on a hike from Homer Tunnel (doh) up a bolder-strewn drainage towards a cascading waterfall. This is the world of the New Zealand Rock Wren, and a rugged world it is. I sat very quietly at a few different spots, and twice found myself at the apparent centre of a pair's territory, seeing 4 birds in total. It is a very cool and different-looking bird, and one worthy of a bigger name, perhaps something like Bob-tailed Bolder-Hopper.

LOCALITY: Mount Aspiring National Park, Mount Earnslaw NZ-Otago (-44.6543,168.3146)
SPECIES COMMENTS: Sighted on the Dart River walking track, Chinamans Bluff locale. Close (within range of 1 - 3 metres), very clear and prolonged sighting. Rock Wren exhibited usual species behaviour, sighted bobbing and foraging on moss covered rocks below the walking track, c.15metres above the river bank. Eliminated Rifleman species as possible identification due to this wrens distinctly taller/upright stance, longer legs, strongly defined white supercilium, vivid yellow flanks & rump, overall size, behaviour hopping /foraging on the rocks. Vocalisation completed confirmed identity as Rock Wren. Noted intense green of the typical male Fiordland morph. --Riflemen were sighted in the Dart River track however not in the same location as the Rock Wren, nor habitat, and certainly quite some distance apart.

Walking up the valley, we heard one followed by several more impossibly tiny, high pitched vocalizations from unseen birds. It was some time of anticipation before James shouted up the slope to say he had one!--Beautiful little bird with an upright, majestic posture standing tall at  tops of large boulders on long pink (unbanded) legs with a virtually absent tail. Looked left and right as it investigated us, bobbing up and down while doing teeny tiny flaps. A big hop and it would look down to pick an insect before looking back at us again, then moving on to the next rock. Every now and again it would stop to lean back and triumphantly peep a teeny tiny peep. This bird covered at least a hundred meters, foraging between rocks and in tiny bushes, with the two of us quietly behind it. --Pale grey brown crown contrasting with a neat whitish supercilium atop a slightly darker and very faint eyeline. Creamy yellow buff underparts with brighter yellow highlights along the flanks. Blackish primary coverts stood out on an otherwise dull greenish wing. Mantle a pale olive brown.--Continuing up the slope we encountered two more colour-banded birds. The first of which was banded orange/white on left blue/alloy on right and obviously unwell with a broken right leg. This bird stood apart from the first with a sharper defined, rich brown crown. The second of these birds, presumably a male, was banded orange/purple, blue/alloy and had a more greenish crown with a more prominent dark patch around the eye.
New Zealand Rock Wren - small wren seems on hike - bobbing on rocks

Long time lifer for Dan 🎉 Absolutely amazing to finally see this species. Heard initially, before a pit came into view and then hopped and flew incredible close to me almost to check me out before carrying on a little further down into the boulder field. A third single male was also seen not too far from here, and two other birds were heard only further up the scree slope. So pumped I did a little dance for joy!
Two males seen again at old car park, and then a pair seen further up in larger boulders foraging. Can’t get enough of how amazing these birds are!

Found flitting around and bobbing up and down on driftwood near a beach boulder field (which seemed liked great South Island Wren habitat, even if the elevation was odd). We got very close (and have photos/video). Larger than Rifleman, without an upturned bill. It also did not behave like a Rifleman: it was much bolder (it got very close to us), was way more terrestrial, and it bobbed up and down each time it landed. Please feel free to contact me if you'd like photos or video.
